DOCUMENT();
loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "Parser.pl",
  "freemanMacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());


Context()->variables->add(t=>'Real');
$pi=arctan(1)*4;
$base=random(2,6,2);
$a=random(1,5,2);
$b=random(2,10,2);
$den=$base+$b;
$densq=$den*$den;
$ans1=$base;
$ans2=-1*$densq/$a;

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
Calculate \(g(b)\) and \(g'(b)\) where \(g(x)\) is the inverse
of \(f(x)=\frac{$a}{x+$b}\),  where \(b=\frac{$a}{$den}\).
$BR
\(g(b)\)=\{ans_rule()\}
$BR
\(g'(b)\)=\{ans_rule()\}
END_TEXT
ANS(num_cmp($ans1));
ANS(num_cmp($ans2));

Context()->normalStrings;
Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$SOL
To determine \(g(b)\), we solve \(f(x)=b\) for \(x\).  This yields:
\(\frac{$a}{x+$b}=\frac{$a}{$den}\), and hence we have \(x+$b=$den\), or \(x=$den-$b=$ans1\).  With
\( f'(x)=\frac{-$a}{(x+$b)^2}\),
it then follows that
\( g'(b)=\frac{1}{f'(g(b))}=\frac{1}{f'($ans1)}=\frac{-$densq}{$a}\).

END_SOLUTION



ENDDOCUMENT();
